HOUSE RESOLUTION 184
By Cepicky
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Edward Allen Hickman
of Columbia.
WHEREAS, the members of this legislative body were greatly saddened to learn of the
passing of Edward Allen Hickman; and
WHEREAS, Eddie Hickman was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on October 28, 1950, in Columbia, Mr. Hickman was the son of Athel
and Evelyn Carpenter Hickman and grew up on Dimple Court alongside his sisters, Donna and
Paula; and
WHEREAS, Eddie Hickman was a 1969 graduate of Columbia Central High School,
where he excelled as a student athlete in both basketball and baseball; from an early age, he
aspired to return to his alma mater to teach and coach; and
WHEREAS, after attending Columbia State Community College, Mr. Hickman graduated
from David Lipscomb University in 1973; he began a lifelong career in education with the Maury
County School System that same year; and
WHEREAS, over the course of his distinguished forty-two-year career, Eddie Hickman
served with dedication and distinction at Hampshire Unit School, Mt. Pleasant High School,
Whitthorne Junior High School, and Columbia Central High School, where he fulfilled his lifelong
dream of teaching and coaching and ultimately served as assistant principal and principal; and
WHEREAS, in 2004, he was appointed to serve as Director of Schools for Maury
County, a role in which he continued to demonstrate steadfast leadership and an unwavering
commitment to the students, educators, and families of the community until his retirement in
2015; and
HR0184
017173
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Mr. Hickman was the recipient of numerous honors throughout his
distinguished career, including designation as a Tennessee Colonel Aide de Camp, the National
High School Coaching Award, WOW Outstanding Citizen Award, A.F. Bridges Tennessee
Secondary School Athletic Association School System Administrator of the Year Award,
Superintendent of the Year for the South-Central Region, recognition as a Paul Harris Fellow,
TSSAA Administrator of the Year Award, and National Association of School Resource Officers
Award, among many others; and
WHEREAS, during his tenure as a coach, Eddie Hickman guided his basketball teams to
appearances in the Tennessee Secondary School Athletic Association substate and state
tournaments; and
WHEREAS, he remained actively engaged in his community in retirement through his
involvement with the Columbia Breakfast Rotary Club, the Tennessee School Resource Officer
Board, COGINA-Advanced Ed, Maury County Retired Teachers Association, and EA
Auctioneering Team; and
WHEREAS, a man of faith, Mr. Hickman was a longtime member of Beech Grove
Church of Christ, where he served in a number of capacities; and
WHEREAS, Eddie Hickman found great joy in spending time with his family and working
on his beloved farm, Mockingbird Hill, where he shared in the simple pleasures of farming,
riding horses, and building lasting memories with his family; and
WHEREAS, he is survived by his loving wife of fifty-six years, Sheila Hutcherson
Hickman; his daughter, Sarah Elizabeth (Sean) Hickman-McLeod; his granddaughter, Ellie
Grace Hickman-McLeod; his sisters, Donna (Tommy) Briggs and Paula (Glenn) Brewer; several
nieces and nephews; special nephew, Bert (Lori) Hutcherson; special niece, Haley (Derrick)
Carroll; his schnauzers, Andy Dog and Sally Anne; and his horse, Red; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Hickman leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
- 2 - 017173

WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we honor the
memory of Edward Allen Hickman, reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his
stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Hickman.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
